BEGIN_PGML
In a science lab, a container had [`21`] ounces of water at 9:00[$NBSP]*AM. Water has been evaporating at the rate of [`3`] ounces every [`5`] minutes. When will there be [`8`] ounces of water left?

[@KeyboardInstructions('Write an equation for this scenario, using [`t`] as the variable. Then do what is needed to clear the denominators. Enter the equation with cleared denominators.')@]**

[_]{$equation}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Since the container has been losing [`3`] oz of water every [`5`] minutes, it loses [`\frac{3}{5}`] oz every minute. At [`t`] minutes past 9:00[$NBSP]*AM, the container will have lost [`\frac{3}{5}t`] oz of water. Since the initial amount was [`21`] oz, the amount of water in the container (in oz) can be modeled by [`21-\frac{3}{5}t\text{.}`]

So to work out when there would be only [`8`] oz of water left, we write the following equation. Note there is a denominator of [`5\text{,}`] which we can clear.

[```\newcommand{\multiplyleft}[2][\cdot]{{\highlight{{#2#1{}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
21-\frac{3}{5}t\amp=8\\
\multiplyleft{5}\left(21-\frac{3}{5}t\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{5}8\\
5\cdot21-5\cdot\frac{3}{5}t\amp=40\\
105-3t\amp=40
\end{aligned}
```]

From here it is straightforward to use steps from Section[$NBSP]*1 to solve the equation. You can try that on your own and you should find that it will take between [`21`] and [`22`] minutes for the container to only have [`8`] ounces of water left.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

